atter explicitly marks \"必須\" in the column while the former doesn't, though both have conditional notes that effectively override this. The knowledge file seems to be consolidating these by dropping the initial \"必須\" designation and leading with the conditional requirement instead, which is arguably a more accurate representation since the note qualifies when the field is actually required.\n\nNow checking the trailer and end records — both have their required fields accounted for. Moving on to the 障害通知 section.\n\nFor the file layout, the knowledge base represents \"0件以上\" (zero or more) as equivalent to the source's note that data records don't need to exist, which is an acceptable interpretation rather than a fabrication. The rest of the specification aligns correctly.\n\nNow checking the section structure—both the source and knowledge file have 4 h2 sections covering functionality overview, entity information, file details, and failure notification specs, so the count is consistent. Moving through the hints verification, s1 contains the expected keywords around user information batches, file input, fixed-length and CSV formats, layout review, and record validation. For s2, the hints list appears to be cut off mid-entry. The `no_knowledge_content` flag is already set to false, so I can skip that validation. Looking more carefully at the details, the source documentation accurately describes the two file input batch types (CSV and fixed-length), which matches what's in the knowledge file. The cross-reference note about additional specifications is just pointing readers to the file info section below, so that checks out.\n\nI'm noticing something interesting with the mobile phone field—the source marks it as unconditionally required but then adds a conditional rule based on the area code field. The knowledge file only captures the conditional requirement, dropping the initial \"required\" designation. It's a judgment call on how to represent conflicting informati